; const veinSize = 8; const discardOnAir = 0.3; // Main thread if (isMainThread) { const worker = new Worker(__filename, { workerData: { world, random, blockPos, veinSize, discardOnAir } }); worker.on('message', (result) => { console.log(result); }); } else { const result = generateNormal(workerData.world, workerData.random, workerData.blockPos, workerData.veinSize, workerData.discardOnAir); parentPort.postMessage(result); } \`\`\` The above Node.js code attempts to simulate the game world and positions while sticking closely to the structure of the original Java code you've given. I've included the basics for running the \`generateNormal\` function in a separate worker thread to avoid blocking the main thread of a Node.js application. This is just a structural representation. The specifics of the game logic are not fully replicated due to missing context and dependencies in your snippet."},{"prompt":"for (int ah = ab; ah <= ae; ++ah) { double ai = ((double) ah + 0.5D - v) / u; if (ai * ai < 1.0D) { for (int aj = ac; aj <= af; ++aj) { double ak = ((double) aj + 0.5D - w) / u; if (ai * ai + ak * ak < 1.0D) { for (int al = ad; al <= ag; ++al) { double am = ((double) al + 0.5D - aa) / u; if (ai * ai + ak * ak + am * am < 1.0D) { int an = ah - x + (aj - y) * size + (al - z) * size * i; if (!bitSet.get(an)) { bitSet.set(an); mutable.set(ah, aj, al); if (aj >= -64 && aj < 320 && (airCheck.get() == AirCheck.OFF || world.getBlockState(mutable).isOpaque())) { if (shouldPlace(world, mutable, discardOnAir, random)) { poses.add(new Vec3d(ah, aj, al)); } } } } } } } } } } Turn this into kotlin and remove the absurd amount of nesting","completion":"To convert this Java code to Kotlin and reduce the nesting, you can use \`continue\` statements to skip iterations when certain conditions are not met. Here's how you could refactor the nested for-loops into Kotlin, focusing on readability and reducing nesting: \`\`\`kotlin for (ah in ab..ae) { val ai = (ah + 0.5 - v) / u if (ai * ai >